<div id="review_170952036" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/170952036" />
    <a title="Bath Book Shop" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5263884-bath-book-shop"><img alt="Bath Book Shop" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1302717663p2/5263884.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/170952036?book_show_action=true">May 25, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bath Book Shop" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bath Book Shop" href="/user/show/5263884-bath-book-shop">Bath Book Shop</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5263884-bath-book-shop?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5263884-bath-book-shop?shelf=chelsea">chelsea</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer170952036" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13037420376568002567">The Adventures of Chelsea and Her Pride and Prejudice Sequels/Retellings (working title) is long and a bit of a downer. (Want the full story? All my reviews, lots of them scathing, are at <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/122606?shelf=janeausten' rel='nofollow noopener'>my &quot;Jane Austen&quot; shelf</a>.) But this one! This one is good!<br/><br/>I knew there were a couple good P&amp;P retellings, simply because of the volume of titles out there. But they are few and far between, and most fall into the &quot;painfully awkward exposition&quot; or &quot;just because you use the same names doesn&apos;t mean they&apos;re the same </span>
  <span id="freeText13037420376568002567" style="display:none">The Adventures of Chelsea and Her Pride and Prejudice Sequels/Retellings (working title) is long and a bit of a downer. (Want the full story? All my reviews, lots of them scathing, are at <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/122606?shelf=janeausten" rel="nofollow noopener">my "Jane Austen" shelf</a>.) But this one! This one is good!<br /><br />I knew there were a couple good P&amp;P retellings, simply because of the volume of titles out there. But they are few and far between, and most fall into the "painfully awkward exposition" or "just because you use the same names doesn't mean they're the same characters if you write them wrong" categories.<br /><br />Hamilton keeps her characters believable and true to Austen's, her story interesting but melodrama-free, and her writing refreshingly free of either random French phrases (*cough*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/83221.Mr__Darcy_Takes_a_Wife_Pride_and_Prejudice_Continues" title="Mr. Darcy Takes a Wife Pride and Prejudice Continues by Linda Berdoll" rel="nofollow noopener">Mr. Darcy Takes a Wife</a>*cough*) or anachronistic speech patterns.<br /><br />A must read for P&amp;P devotees, even the ones who are a bit jaded by all the failed attempts they've already sat through.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13037420376568002567" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


